@NODE "I" "What is it?"
@NEXT "II"
@PREV "Main"
@TOC "MAIN"

                              I. What is it?

TMaker is a tiny useful test in HTML code creator. It allows you to create
test in HTML code without knowing the code itself. The tests are designed to
be conducted on-line, however you can also simply print them out, and conduct
in in traditional way.
Tests are designed in multiple choice question style. I mainly aim this
software to the teachers, but you can also use it, if you want to design
a part of your web page (survey for example).
@ENDNODE

@NODE "II" "Requirements"
@NEXT "III"
@PREV "I"
@TOC "MAIN"

                             II. Requirements.

Any Amiga with any version of AmigaOS. It should run even on the simplest
configurations. All you need is about 50 KB of free RAM.
Those are the requirements of TMaker itself, but you'll need something more,
to be able to take advantage of all the possibilities the TMaker gives you.

Optional:
- any web browser, for viewing the HTML version of the tests created
- TCP/IP Internet connection for conducting the online tests (any AmiTCP
  compatible TCP/IP stack should be enough)
- any web browser capable of sending emails properly, conducting the on-line
  tests
- printer, for printing the tests or answer keys
@ENDNODE

@NODE "III" "How to use it"
@NEXT "1"
@PREV "II"
@TOC "MAIN"

                            III. How to use it.

After running TMaker, new console should open, which will contain the welcome
menu will see a welcome menu.

Now, you can choose any of the following options, by pressing the proper key
(1, 2, 3 etc.).

                            1. @{"Create new test." LINK "1"}
                              2. @{"Print test." LINK "2"}
                           3. @{"Print answer key." LINK "3"}
                              4. @{"Information." LINK "4"}
                                 5. @{"Quit." LINK "5"}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "1" "Create new test"
@NEXT "2"
@PREV "III"
@TOC "III"

                            1. Create new test.

The option starts the creation of a new test. After choosing the option, you
will be prompted to enter a path to the file, where a new test should be
written. The path should be entered in typical DOS way, which is for example 
DH0:Mytests/New_ones/TestNo1. The path should end with filename and no
extension is needed. TMaker will add the proper file extension itself
(*.html or *.txt).

NOTE: if you type the path to the already existing file, it will be overwritten.
Next you will be prompted to enter the number of questions, the test will
contain. Just enter the number (12) for example, and press Enter. Then you
will be prompted to type in the test's title. The title you will type is
printed at the top of the page (either in text or HTML mode). Usually the
subject of the test should be entered here, for example "Irregular verbs".
Next you need to enter your (author's of the test) name. The name you enter is
used to fill in the necessary META fields in HTML file. If you don't want to
givee your name don't type anything, just press Enter and you will move to the
next step.
Now, you have to type in your email address. Email is necessary for conducting
the online test, since you will receive your students' answer to the address
you type here. If you are not going to conduct the test in online mode, just
press Enter without typing anything. Now you have to type time needed for
completing the test. It will be printed on the top of the test, under the
title, so your students will know how much time they have.

NOTE: time must be entered in minutes, using numbers only.

Next you have an option to type in any extra notifications concerning the
test. Anything you type here, will be printed under the time given for doing
the test.

Now you will start to create the test itself. First you have to enter the
question, after being prompted to do so.
When TMaker says, for example, "Type in question number 1:" you should write
for instance "I ..... leaving tomorrow morning. Aren't I". Then you have to
type four possible answers (it's a multiple choice questions test, as it was
said before). Sticking to the example given before (concerning typing in the
question), you can write four possible answer which might look like this: am,
should, am going, will (answer number one is a correct answer as you can see).
After typing in four possible answers, you have to let the TMaker know, which
answer is a correct one (it should be written, using numbers from 1 to 4
only). In our example it will be "1" of course.
Typing the correct answer is vital for correcting the test. The numbers you
enter are used to create the answer key (which you may print out then).
You will need to repeat the steps concerning creating the question in your
test, as many times, as the questions number specified at the beginning of the
creation.
After whole operation is finished, proper messages giving you the paths to the
files will be printed at the bottom of the page. TMaker will create three
different files:

- HTML file, containing the HTML version of your test, needed for online
  purposes
- text file, containing the text version of your test, which is just and
  addon, for main idea of the software. You can print out this text version,
  after returning to main menu screen.
- text file, containing the answer key for your test. You can print the answer
  key, after returning to the main menu screen now.

After pressing any key, you will return to the main menu screen now.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "2" "Print test"
@NEXT "3"
@PREV "1"
@TOC "III"

                              2. Print test.

Choosing this option allows you to print out previously designed test. After
pressing the "2" key, you will be prompted to turn on the printer, and press
any key.
After doing so, the printing operation starts, and you are prompted to press
any key, to return to main menu screen.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "3" "Print answer key"
@NEXT "4"
@PREV "2"
@TOC "III"

                           3. Print answer key.

This option is similar to the previously described one. Choosing it allows you
to print out the answer key for the previously designed test. Whole operation
is exactly the same as in the case of printing the test (point 2), so no need
to describe it here again.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "4" "Information"
@NEXT "5"
@PREV "3"
@TOC "III"

                              4. Information.

This option prints out few useful information about TMaker. You can see the
version number here, @{"my" LINK "VIII"} email address, registration number and few more things.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "5" "Quit"
@NEXT "IV"
@PREV "4"
@TOC "III"

                                 5. Quit.

Choosing this option quits the TMaker. You have to confirm the operation by
pressing the "Y" key (or decline it with "N" or any other key). After then the
goodbye message will be printed, and you will be prompted to press any key, to
shut down the program completely.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "IV" "Conducting test online"
@NEXT "V"
@PREV "5"
@TOC "MAIN"

                        IV. Conducting test online.

Conducting the test online was the main idea I had, when I created this piece
of software. Such an attempt limits your work as a teacher greatly, since you
don't have to carry out all those papers all the way to the place you work at,
and then back to home.
It also allows me to design and create a piece of software, that would read
the incoming answers, correct the test, and give you the percentage of correct
answer. It is even possible to make it mark the test, after you enter the
necessary guidelines. Future versions of Tmaker should have this ability.
How to conduct such a test? Here are some things, that are vital in this case:

- computerized classroom
- TCP/IP Internet connection
- any web browser installed on every machine (capable of sending emails)

Now, all you have to do, is to bring the HTML file, created with TMaker with
you. Then copy it to every machine in the classroom. You can also copy it to
your main computer (usually in such a classrooms, there's one central machine,
designed for teacher's use), and make it (the file) accessible via LAN
connection (I don't even imagine an computerized classroom without a set up
LAN connection). You can even place the file in the Internet, if you have the
possibility (you will need an account on a WWW server of course).
There are many ways, and it's up to you, which will you choose. You only have
to make the file accessible on every machine in the classroom.
Next you open the file in the web browser on every machine (or just tell your
students to do so), and let your students to choose the correct answers. After
doing so, all one has to do is to fill in his name, and press the "Finished"
button, at the bottom of the page.
That's it. The answers should be sent to your email account, and you can
download them all, after coming home.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "V" "Distribution"
@NEXT "VI"
@PREV "IV"
@TOC "MAIN"

                             V. Distribution.

TMaker is an emailware software, which means you don't have to pay for it, but
if you run it at least twice, you must send me an email (you can include your
notices, opinions etc.).
@{"My" LINK "VIII"} email address is sirhaker@interia.pl. Reply is guaranteed. All emails
encourage me to develop TMaker and fit it with new features.
You can copy and distribute TMaker, as long as the whole package is intact.
You mustn't change the contents of the package!

@ENDNODE

